
test_rsa: Perform RSA operations

Currently supported features:
 - Key generation (no CRT)
 - PSS signing and verification

Load the container and the following usage will also be shown in the logs:

CI: Usage: cmtest cmd COMMAND [arguments]
CI: COMMAND: keygen|pss_sign|pss_verify

CI: keygen MODSIZE PUBE
CI: Generate an RSA keypair.
CI: Outputs PUBN||PRIVD
CI: PUBN and PRIVD are MODBITS/8 bytes long
CI: MODSIZE:  length in bits of the RSA modulus. Must be multiple of 8,
              maximum is 8192
CI: PUBE:     RSA public key exponent. Must be 4 bytes long

CI: pss_sign MODSIZE HASHALGO SALTLEN PUBN PUBE PRIVD MSG
CI: Sign a message or a digest with RSA-PSS.
CI: Outputs the pss signature, which is MODSIZE/8 bytes long.
CI: MODSIZE:  length in bits of RSA modulus. See keygen command
CI: HASHALGO: hash algorithm to use or "prehashed" if msg is a digest
CI: SALTLEN:  length in bytes of the PSS salt. Can be 0 for deterministic sigs
CI: PUBN:     n component of pubkey. Must be MODSIZE/8 bytes long
CI: PUBE:     e component of pubkey (exponent). Must be 4 bytes long
CI: PRIVD:    d component of private key. Must be MODSIZE/8 bytes long
CI: MSG:      message (or digest if prehashed) to sign
CI:           Max len is MODSIZE/8. If prehashed, the len of digest
              is the hash len

CI: pss_verify MODSIZE HASHALGO SALTLEN PUBN PUBE SIG MSG
CI: outputs a u32 little-endian value. 0 on valid signature.
CI: Sign a message or a digest with RSA-PSS.
CI: MODSIZE:  length in bits of RSA modulus. See keygen command
CI: HASHALGO: hash algorithm to use or "prehashed" if msg is a digest
CI: SALTLEN:  length in bytes of the PSS salt. Can be 0 for deterministic sigs
CI: PUBN:     n component of pubkey. Must be MODSIZE/8 bytes long
CI: PUBE:     e component of pubkey (exponent). Must be 4 bytes long
CI: SIG:      pss signature blob, the output of pss_sign
CI: MSG:      message (or digest if prehashed) to verify with SIG
CI:           Max len is MODSIZE/8. If prehashed, the len of digest
              is the hash len

CI: NOTE:     If "-" is provided as SALTLEN, hash len is used as salt len.

CI: oaep_encrypt MODSIZE HASHALGO PUBN PUBE MSG
CI: Encrypts a message with OAEP RSA.
CI: Returns an encrypted message with length MODSIZE/8.
CI: MODSIZE:  length in bits of RSA modulus. See keygen command
CI: HASHALGO: hash algorithm to use
CI: PUBN:     n component of pubkey. Must be MODSIZE/8 bytes long
CI: PUBE:     e component of pubkey (exponent). Must be 4 bytes long
CI: LABEL:    optional parameter used to add an additional input to
              the encryption process
CI: MSG:      message to encrypt with OAEP RSA

CI: oaep_decrypt MODSIZE HASHALGO PUBN PUBE PRIVD ENCMSG
CI: Decrypts a message previously encrypted with OAEP RSA.
CI: Returns a plaintext message.
CI: MODSIZE:  length in bits of RSA modulus. See keygen command
CI: HASHALGO: hash algorithm to use
CI: PUBN:     n component of pubkey. Must be MODSIZE/8 bytes long
CI: PUBE:     e component of pubkey (exponent). Must be 4 bytes long
CI: PRIVD:    d component of private key. Must be MODSIZE/8 bytes long
CI: LABEL:    optional parameter used to add an additional input to
              the encryption process
CI: ENCMSG:   encrypted message to decrypt

CI: Available HASHALGO:

CI: sha224 (len 28 bytes)
CI: sha256 (len 32 bytes)
CI: sha384 (len 48 bytes)
CI: sha512 (len 64 bytes)
CI: sha512_224 (len 28 bytes)
CI: sha512_256 (len 32 bytes)
CI: sha3_224 (len 28 bytes)
CI: sha3_256 (len 32 bytes)
CI: sha3_384 (len 48 bytes)
CI: sha3_512 (len 64 bytes)
CI: shake128 (len 16 bytes)
CI: shake256 (len 32 bytes)
CI: whirlpool (len 28 bytes)

# Examples

## Load the container

$ mwtest.py -c100 run test_rsa.img

## Generate a key

$ time cmtest cmd -t30000 -f100 keygen 2048 %01000100 > /tmp/key2048
Sending data to CMRT via SIC...
...received 512 bytes OK

real    0m21.068s

### Extracting the components of the key

First half of output is PUBN, second half is PRIVD.

$ dd bs=256 count=1 if=/tmp/key2048 of=/tmp/key2048_pubn
$ dd bs=256 skip=1 count=1 if=/tmp/key2048 of=/tmp/key2048_privd

Notice that PUBN and PRIVD are each modsize bits in length.

$ wc -c /tmp/key2048*
 512 /tmp/key2048
 256 /tmp/key2048_privd
 256 /tmp/key2048_pubn

## Signing a message

Since "-" is provided as the salt length, the hash length will be used
as salt length, in this case 32. Any value between 0 and 64 (both
included) is valid. A salt length of 0 will always produce the same
signature for the same message and key.

If HASHALGO "prehashed" is used, then the message is expected to already
be a digest, and its length is considered the length of the digest.

$ cmtest cmd -f100 pss_sign 2048 sha256 - %`xxd -p -c256 /tmp/key2048_pubn` %01000100 %`xxd -p -c256 /tmp/key2048_privd` "Hello World" > /tmp/sig
Sending data to CMRT via SIC...
...received 256 bytes OK

Note that if you prefix an argument with '%', the cmtest utility hex decodes
it before sending it to the CMRT.

$ wc -c /tmp/sig
256 /tmp/sig

## Verifying the signature

$ cmtest cmd -f100 pss_verify 2048 sha256 - %`xxd -p -c256 /tmp/key2048_pubn` %01000100 %`xxd -p -c256 /tmp/sig` "Hello World"
Sending data to CMRT via SIC...
...received 4 bytes OK
00000000: 00 00 00 00                                       |....|

The returned value of 0 means the signature is valid.
With invalid signature the returned value would be nonzero.

$ cmtest cmd -f100 pss_verify 2048 sha256 - %`xxd -p -c256 /tmp/key2048_pubn` %01000100 %`xxd -p -c256 /tmp/sig` "Wrong message"

Sending data to CMRT via SIC...
...received 4 bytes OK
00000000: ff ff ff ff                                       |....|

## Encrypting a plaintext message

$ cmtest cmd -f100 oaep_encrypt 2048 sha256 %`xxd -p -c256 /tmp/key2048_pubn` %01000100 "label" "plaintext message" > /tmp/encrypted_msg
Sending data to CMRT via SIC...
...received 256 bytes OK

## Decrypting an encrypted message

$ cmtest cmd -f100 oaep_decrypt 2048 sha256 %`xxd -p -c256 /tmp/key2048_pubn` %01000100 %`xxd -p -c256 /tmp/key2048_privd` "label" %`xxd -p -c256 /tmp/encrypted_msg` > /tmp/plaintext
Sending data to CMRT via SIC...
...received 17 bytes OK

## To verify that the message is correctly decrypted

$ cat /tmp/plaintext
plaintext message

## To unload container:
$ mwtest.py -c100 unload
